{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_122","type":"agent_message","text":"Completed the full research run. The main outputs are [REPORT.md](/workspaces/interp-incongruent-79b3-codex/REPORT.md), [README.md](/workspaces/interp-incongruent-79b3-codex/README.md), [planning.md](/workspaces/interp-incongruent-79b3-codex/planning.md), and the pipeline in [src/run_research.py](/workspaces/interp-incongruent-79b3-codex/src/run_research.py).\n\nThe key result is narrower than the original hypothesis: incongruent interpolation is not uniformly more unstable. In the matched SugarCrepe study, `replace_relation` behaves like genuine incongruence and increases off-manifold deviation and dual-space path length, but `swap_object` and `swap_atribute` often do the opposite because the negative caption is lexically closer to the source than the paraphrase control. The LRH-style control still recovered a separable regime for curated concept pairs, so the final conclusion is that interpolation failure tracks relational/structural incompatibility more than contradiction alone.\n\nArtifacts are in [results](/workspaces/interp-incongruent-79b3-codex/results) and [figures](/workspaces/interp-incongruent-79b3-codex/figures). I validated the generated tables and counts after the run; the matched comparison is 225 `(subset, example_id)` pairs and 450 total path rows. One metric was not useful: the sampled k-NN graph made `detour_ratio` collapse to `1.0`, and that limitation is documented in the report. There were also pre-existing unrelated workspace changes in `git status` that I did not modify."}}
